d><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;\">Extension<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">72 \u00baC \/ 45 s<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">35<\/td><\/tr><tr><td style = \"text-align:center;\">6<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;\">Final extension<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">72 \u00baC \/ 5 min<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">1<\/td><\/tr><tr><td style = \"text-align:center;\">7<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;\">Hold<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">4 \u00baC<\/td><td rowspan = \"\" colspan = \"\" style =\"display : table-cell;text-align:center;\">--<\/td><\/tr><\/table>"}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"A3930961E9CF49F8A8763EE76AD82F36","order_id":5,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmiba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA9F6C","section_duration":28800,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079824,"guid":"408D37802CED11EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079801,"previous_guid":"64AE2AB02CE911EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"2D574524781A481C8C49FB1F959A48F5","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"AADB12B091AE4BCF9F0F06F3EC4C1890","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Prepare 2% agarose gel. For 35 mL of agarose gel, mix 0.7 g of agarosa and 35 mL of buffer tris-borate-EDTA (TBE). Heat in microwave until complete disolution of agarose. Let it cool down (65 \u00baC approx.), pour it in the mold and place the comb to make wells. Let it cool down to room temperature and take it out of the mold when ready to run the PCR amplification products.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmkba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"2815BA4D5D6D487BB3D4AB200436DA10","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmkba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079825,"guid":"F30595002CEE11EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079824,"previous_guid":"408D37802CED11EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"79EF97EF4B2E4422B893A4293A58528E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"6D47378BFCC34B2E9018FC13919F4861","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Prepare enough loading buffer for the number of samples to run (1 \u03bcL of loading buffer per sample).<\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Perform this procedure in the pre-PCR cabinet. Use a 1.5-mL vial to mix 1 mL of loading buffer 6X with 1 \u03bcL of red gel. Shake well and keep refrigerated and protected from light until used.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079826,"guid":"1A595F502CF011EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079825,"previous_guid":"F30595002CEE11EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"4DF17CFC498049F588E1A5CA83C2697C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"17210AD45A8B46CD85E5FCBC4AC696E1","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Place the 2% agarose gel in the electrophoresis chamber. Fill the electrophoresis chamber with enough 1X buffer TBE until it slightly goes over the agarose gel. On the benchtop, use a parafilm fragment and pour 1 \u03bcL aliquots of loading buffer across the parafilm.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmqba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Take 5 \u03bcL of each sample to run. After that, set the pipette volume to 8-10 \u03bcL and carefully absorb the loading buffer with the aid of the pipette, mixing gently several times. Load the sample in the corresponding well of the agarose gel. Change pipette tips between samples, blank and positive control. <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">DO NOT USE THIS PROCEDURE to load DNA ladder since it is ready to use. The DNA ladder (6 \u03bcL<\/span><span>) <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">is loaded directly into the corresponding well.<\/span><span><\/span><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmuba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"A5DA3B1003184C11A9F3D2D36F9D640D","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmqba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"50E091435F1744569DDD268435D37AB9","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmuba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079848,"guid":"F979C9902CF511EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079826,"previous_guid":"1A595F502CF011EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"A5247866CCBE44809313493E49BB324A","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"57C2E8E3E6CD4371BD30AEF9933D60E8","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Close the electrophoresis chamber and connect it to its power source. The wells on the gel should always be on the negative side of the chamber. Set voltage to 80 V and running time to 50 min and start the run.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079849,"guid":"B1C114902CF611EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079848,"previous_guid":"F979C9902CF511EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F665D31D015C416E89B931FAAEF1E64C","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3AAF6F6C35DB4A39A7ED2AFB2B99D196","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Once the electrophoresis is finished, turn off the power supply and get the gel out of the chamber. Tilt the gel tray over the chamber to remove the excess TBE buffer from the gel. Bring the gel to the photo-documentation system.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079850,"guid":"5ADF25D02CF711EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079849,"previous_guid":"B1C114902CF611EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"D041B5911C98405E8ECFF749831F8285","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5D4D7B35C5A24156AAC86902E2E914CB","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Open the photo-documentation device and clean it with 70% alcohol before placing the gel to be documented. Use a disposable paper towel to dry any excess of alcohol left on the surface.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079851,"guid":"C4A3B7602CF711EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079850,"previous_guid":"5ADF25D02CF711EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"42225DCAB4934D93B6AA0E2C81A8F070","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"5. Visualization of PCR-amplified fragments"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"1E8C75101EEB4798850487CFDD136944","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Place the gel on the clean surface of the photo-documentation system, close the cabinet and turn it on. Open the gel documentation software in the connected computer. Use the program to digitalize the gel image. Edit the image to identify each of the lanes (DNA ladder, blank, positive control, samples) and save it. The file name of the image is composed as follows: project initials_date_number_of_samples_in_that_run. For example, if documenting samples 1 to 20 of \"Project1\" on November 18, 2020, the file name must be:  project1_111820_1to20.jpeg<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmwba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"FBA3D147E9AF4E3DA636E5FC7AF3FF91","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgmwba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#E57785","section_duration":14400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079852,"guid":"6C12C3A02CF911EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079851,"previous_guid":"C4A3B7602CF711EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"DF76D745FCE344A7A30031DE0AF01DAC","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"6. Selective plating, isolation and final identity confirmation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"3BEE923DEFB54611872F62376BEC64F6","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Selective enriched samples that were negative in the PCR test are discarded. For positive samples, take 100 \u03bcL from each selective enrichment broth and streak it in duplicates in XLT-4 and Salmonella CHROMagar plates.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA94FF","section_duration":259200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079853,"guid":"05C821202CFA11EB8A84C520E7197197","previous_id":1079852,"previous_guid":"6C12C3A02CF911EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"5D6AE9D8779C4DE093BDFE393DC1C67B","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"6. Selective plating, isolation and final identity confirmation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"55901882A5234CB3A2FAB0ECA80F65FF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Incubate plates at 35 \u00b1 1 \u00baC\/ 24 \u00b1 2 h. After incubation, check for colonies with typical <\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">Salmonella<\/span><span> morphology. <\/span><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgm6ba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgm8ba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"092FECF491804CA1BFE6E9F9EBF06BF1","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgm6ba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"C3A66716EBF94EBDB80440A129EDE30A","order_id":3,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgm8ba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA94FF","section_duration":259200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079856,"guid":"DC522B602CFE11EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079853,"previous_guid":"05C821202CFA11EB8A84C520E7197197","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"AC291E9E828A41DBBA6C599A82A1C1BC","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"6. Selective plating, isolation and final identity confirmation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DB7C1D70A2F642D58C4C2BDE8C4531EF","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Pick at least 3 typical isolated colonies from each selective agar for final PCR identity confirmation. Mix each isolated colony in 1 mL of molecular grade water. Afterwards, conduct steps 8-12 of section 3, as well as all steps from sections 4 and 5 of this protocol.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA94FF","section_duration":259200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079857,"guid":"01130B402CFF11EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079856,"previous_guid":"DC522B602CFE11EBB3B79B5DDA220043","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"9E69F87CC1C4440681DFA77AF2788024","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"6. Selective plating, isolation and final identity confirmation"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"2DA22F1CB4054A81B10A1F2AFCD08307","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Only for samples with positive results in final PCR confirmation:<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Pick some growth from the same colonies used for final PCR confirmation and streak it into TSA agar plates. Incubate at 37 \u00baC \/ 24 h. Afterwards, pick isolated colonies from the TSA agar plate and preserve pure isolates, as described below. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#EA94FF","section_duration":259200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079858,"guid":"289DC4102D0011EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079857,"previous_guid":"01130B402CFF11EBB3B79B5DDA220043","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"44A42C355C7844449FE1B43FE8224EBF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"7. Preservation of pure isolates"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"38C8745F199F406BBFA65815AD048573","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Deep frozen storage<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">With a sterilized inoculation loop, pick isolated colonies from TSA agar plates and transfer them to  5-mL Falcon tubes containing 2 mL of sterile BHI broth. Place the tubes in a shaking incubator at 37 \u00baC for 24 h and 150 rpm. After incubation, add 0.4 mL of sterile glycerol to each tube, mix well and store at - 80 \u00baC.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgnaba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"8A2F7570BF8A4A619E28C6E0205483DB","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgnaba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":172800,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079859,"guid":"42A567202D0311EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079858,"previous_guid":"289DC4102D0011EBB3B79B5DDA220043","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"36C2380EFAE844708FA125568948BFC3","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"7. Preservation of pure isolates"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"343306A558214D11B8194F1B85A0CA99","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Room temperature storage<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">With a sterilized inoculation loop, pick isolated colonies from TSA agar plates and inoculate them into TSA slants. To do that, first stab the center of the medium on the lowest part of the slant. Then, take the loop out and streak on the surface of the agar slant, moving outwards. Fill up to 3\/4 of the streaked tubes with mineral oil. Close the tubes and seal the caps with parafilm. Keep pure isolates at room temperature.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":172800,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079864,"guid":"1AA8D5802D0911EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079647,"previous_guid":"67A4B8602C7B11EBAB54737C6B5D7F8D","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"092221F2D7134777ADE6A7A986B8A2C0","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"1.1 Pre-enrichment of surface water samples"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"C21161234E254885BDAD85A248D898C5","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Place the bags in a shaking incubator at 36-37 \u00baC \/ 18-20 h \/ 150 rpm.<\/div><div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgncba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"9B4841D1EA154F4F838510DF4CBDFB3A","order_id":2,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div style = \"text-align :; float : ;\"><img style = \"\" src = \"https:\/\/s3.amazonaws.com\/protocols-files\/files\/dgncba9mf.jpg\" \/><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":86400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079865,"guid":"07EE69402D0A11EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079648,"previous_guid":"E09E75202C7C11EBAB54737C6B5D7F8D","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"3CB39F2B4550474EA7421D8684E0831A","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"1.2 Pre-enrichment of meat and lymph node samples"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"43F18F64F593455498A02F13884E18CA","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Meat cuts, minced meat or ground meat:<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\">Aseptically weight 25 g of meat and grind it for 30 s in a sterile Oster blender. Aseptically transfer the ground meat to a Stomacher bag, add 225 mL of BPW and homogenize for 1 min. If dealing with ground meat, skip the grinding step. Let the homogenized sample stand for 2 h at room temperature before incubating at 36-37 \u00baC \/ 18-20 h. <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":86400,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1079874,"guid":"BD33F1B02D2511EBB3B79B5DDA220043","previous_id":1079859,"previous_guid":"42A567202D0311EBB3B79B5DDA220043","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"AB23C943E461477784E3D652F2932502","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Disposal of wastes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"549E0ECFF87944EB96E69343E4798FA6","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Discard all generated residues according to current procedure to handle hazardous wastes.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#94EBFF","section_duration":0,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"","changed_on":1620317162}